metadata.name: Flow 2 #51
metadata.description:
This series is a collection of animations based on noise fields and fluid dynamics. The pieces are designed to run continuously, and they produce slowly evolving images that seem to drip, swirl, pulse, and flow. Dense networks of patterns emerge and decay as the pieces evolve. Because of their subtle movement, these works make excellent wall art when run on a display monitor.

Flow 2 is somewhat less chaotic and more meditative than the original. It employs different brushstrokes and a different decay algorithm. I also added a number of new color palettes, now 35 in all.

While these animations are most interesting to view at larger sizes, if your performance begins to suffer just reduce the size of your viewing window.

-spacebar will pause the animation

-return will resume the animation

-r will restart the animation

Flow 2, 2022
-hieroglyphica

metadata.name: Slanted #115
metadata.description:
Fun little game, simple rules:
- start with a randomly sized grid
- pick 2 random cells
- recursively, every cell draw itself
- then it picks two of its neighbors for the next step

Some cells are drawn multiple times, some others are never picked up, but the process it's not completely random.

metadata.name: Greetings From Habitable Zones #12
metadata.description:
178 abstract post cards from 21 potentially habitable exoplanets.

"Greetings From Habitable Zones" is influenced by 70s retro poster aesthetics, Impressionism and the infinite vastness of space.
The palette consists of 11 carefully chosen colors which can occur randomly in every part of the piece.
Detailed information about the exoplanet can be found in the features section of the respective token.

///

Press "s" in live view to save a png of your post card.

The music was written and recorded on November 14th, 2020 on a Tascam 4-track tape recorder.

Data source: phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog

metadata.name: Concrete #285
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Corinth #46
metadata.description:
In art, and in generative art especially, we often find ourselves with loose ends, experiments that don't make the final piece. These go often unappreciated and are left unpublished and unseen. When making my last project Mycenae I (re)discovered a number of related attractors. Rhea has sharp corners in place of sweeping arcs. Phoebe turns back on itself, long curves join at harsh vertices. 

Both strange attractors are fractals, containing infinite detail. The token contains the generation parameters and so represents the fractal at a deeper level than the image itself. 

I included my debug renderer as an Easter egg. You would be lucky to find it.

The naming comes from a convention I have picked up from habit. Coding projects are named for Greek figures of myth. Generative tokens should be named for ancient centres of Greek civilisation. The attractors I named for titans and, since they are all related, Saturnian moons.

metadata.name: Voice #5

metadata.name: MOYO #58
metadata.description:
MOYO is generative piece building unique patterns.
The first algorithm was created in 2018, while visiting Kanazawa, a city on the west side of Japan.
Originally inspired by some kimono embroidery, I created some set of rules that will give life, recursively, to patterns generated inside a squared area.

Thanks to fxhash, I can pursue the original generative vision of those patterns by evolving the algorithm, and here comes MOYO.
This collection of 1024 pieces waiting to be minted offers new compositions, new rules and new colors.
During the iterative crafting process, I've been surprised by the algorithm which offered some unexpected kind of results, which have been kept for the final generation.

Artist: Florian Zumbrunn
@florianzumbrunn
